Start by writing the flux of the wire’s field through the rectangular loop.  At a distance r from a long straight wire carrying current \(I_{0}\) the field is

 \(B(r)=\dfrac{\mu_{0}I_{0}}{2\pi\,r}\)

and (by the right‐hand rule) it points into the page everywhere to the right of the wire.  If the near edge of the loop is at \(x\) and the far edge at \(x+b\), the flux through the loop (height \(a\)) is

\[
\Phi(x)\;=\;\int_{r=x}^{x+b}B(r)\,a\,dr
\;=\;\int_x^{x+b}\frac{\mu_{0}I_{0}}{2\pi\,r}\,a\,dr
\;=\;\frac{\mu_{0}I_{0}a}{2\pi}\,\ln\!\frac{x+b}{x}\,.
\]

Since the loop is being pulled to the right with speed \(v\), \(x\) is increasing in time, and there is an induced emf

\[
\mathcal{E}
\;=\;
-\frac{d\Phi}{dt}
\;=\;
-\frac{d\Phi}{dx}\,\frac{dx}{dt}
\;=\;
-\frac{d}{dx}\!\Big[
\frac{\mu_{0}I_{0}a}{2\pi}\ln\frac{x+b}{x}
\Big]\,v
\;.
\]
Compute
\[
\frac{d}{dx}\ln\frac{x+b}{x}
\;=\;\frac{1}{x+b}-\frac{1}{x}
\;=\;-\,\frac{b}{x(x+b)}\,,
\]
so

\[
\mathcal{E}
\;=\;
-\Big[
\frac{\mu_{0}I_{0}a}{2\pi}
\Big]\Big(-\frac{b}{x(x+b)}\Big)\,v
\;=\;
\frac{\mu_{0}I_{0}\,a\,b\,v}{2\pi\,x(x+b)}\,.
\]
Finally the induced current in a resistor \(R\) is
\[
I_{\rm ind}(x)
\;=\;
\frac{\mathcal{E}}{R}
\;=\;
\frac{\mu_{0}\,I_{0}\,a\,b\,v}
     {2\pi\,R\,x\,(x+b)}\,.
\]

By Lenz’s law the sign of this current is such as to try to maintain the “into‐the‐page” flux which is decreasing, i.e. it circulates clockwise when the loop is viewed from above (the side of the wire).
